#include<stdio.h>

int main()
{
    int a[100], n, i, j, temp;

    printf("Enter no of elements: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    printf("Enter elements:\n");

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        scanf("%d", &a[i]);
    }

    // Insertion Sort
    for(i = 1; i < n; i++)
    {
        temp = a[i];
        j = i - 1;

        while(j >= 0 && a[j] > temp)
        {
            a[j + 1] = a[j];
            j--;
        }

        a[j + 1] = temp;
    }

    printf("Sorted elements are:\n");

    for(i = 0; i < n; i++)
    {
        printf("%d ", a[i]);
    }

    return 0;
}

/*

Insertion Sort in C

This program sorts elements in ascending order using the Insertion Sort technique.

Algorithm Idea

Insertion Sort works like arranging playing cards in hand.

Assume the first element is already sorted.

Take the next element (temp).

Compare it with previous elements.

Shift larger elements one position to the right.

Insert the element in the correct position.

Repeat until all elements are sorted.


Time Complexity

Best Case: O(n) → already sorted

Average Case: O(n²)

Worst Case: O(n²) → reverse order


Key Variables

temp → stores current element

j → compares previous elements

a[j+1] = a[j] → shifting process


Advantages

Simple and easy to understand

Efficient for small datasets

Stable sorting algorithm

Works well for nearly sorted arrays


Applications

Small data sorting

Online sorting

Used in hybrid sorting algorithms


Example

Input:

5
5 3 4 1 2

Output:

1 2 3 4 5

Logic Flow

Pick element → Compare → Shift larger elements → Insert correctly

Memory Trick

“Take one element and insert it into its correct position in the sorted part.”*/